# Git workflow

## Commits

- Conventional Commits: semantic subject + audit-useful rationale in the body.
- One logical change per commit: touch only the files required for that change;
  commit independent concerns separately.
- Outside plan mode, auto-commit completed work without asking — commits flow
  automatically in implementation mode. Pause and return to plan mode only if a
  fundamental design issue surfaces, or when the user pushes back on a recent change.
- Commit/PR audit trailers (Authored-By, Model, Session-ID, …) → my-audit-trail.

## Push / pull

- Push immediately after every commit, same turn — don't wait to be asked.
- Pull-rebase-before-push: always `git pull --rebase` before `git push`; on a
  non-fast-forward rejection, retry once with `git pull --rebase && git push`.
- Auto-proceed on read-only ops (status, diff, log, show, branch, pull, push,
  push --force-with-lease) without asking.

## Destructive ops — pause first

Pause before push --force, push --delete, rebase, reset, stash pop/drop, tag
unless the user explicitly requested that exact action in the current message.

## Stashes

Always `git stash push -m "<unique-slug>"` — never bare `git stash`. Pop by name.
Multiple agents share the stash stack; unnamed stashes collide.

## Uncommitted edits already on main → stash into a worktree

The user sometimes edits files directly on `main` and asks you to review and commit them.
Commits on the main checkout are hook-blocked. **Do not** request a `worktree-exempt` file —
move the changes into a worktree via the shared stash stack:

1. **Create a worktree** (create mechanics below). cwd is now the worktree, so git against the
   main checkout is allowed via `git -C <main>` (`<main>` = parent of `git rev-parse --git-common-dir`).
2. **Stash main's changes:** `git -C <main> stash push -m "<slug>"` — named per `## Stashes`,
   guard-inert because cwd is the worktree. Main's working tree is now clean.
3. **Pull them into the worktree:** `git stash list` to find the `stash@{n}` matching `<slug>`,
   then `git stash apply stash@{n}`. The stash stack is shared via the common git dir.
4. **Review, commit in the worktree, and merge back** per the protocol below. If the root thread
   can't run Bash to commit, see *Committing from a worktree when the root thread can't run Bash*.
5. **After the commit is verified,** `git -C <main> stash drop stash@{n}`. Apply-then-drop keeps
   the stash as a backup until the commit lands; `pop` would discard it on the spot.

- *Stash won't apply cleanly* (local main was ahead of origin and the worktree branched fresh):
  resolve the conflicts, or recreate the worktree from local `HEAD` so the edits apply onto the
  state they were made against.

## Multi-instance worktrees (mandatory before any file edit)

Concurrent agents on one branch race (last write wins); Write/Edit/Bash are
hook-blocked on the main checkout until inside a worktree.

1. `git pull`, then check claims: `todo.sh list @worktree`.
2. Create a worktree and work inside it.
3. Record the claim in todo.txt and commit it in the worktree's first commit.
   ← todo.txt format: my-task-tracking.

### Completing the worktree — merge-back

The worktree guard only restricts git whose **cwd is the main checkout**. So run every step
below from **inside the worktree** (where all git is allowed) and advance main via
`git -C <main> …` — the guard stays inert and the whole flow is agent-doable. The only
human-only action is creating a `worktree-exempt` file; never create one. `<main>` = the
primary checkout (the parent of `git rev-parse --git-common-dir`).

1. **Finish & verify.** Commit your work. Run the project's automated gates (e.g.
   `mise run lint && mise run test`, or the repo's equivalents) and fix failures — see
   `my-linting`, `my-testing`.

2. **Open the PR as a draft, early.** As soon as you have a commit to push:
   - *GitHub (any owner):* `git push -u origin <branch>`; `gh pr create --draft --fill`. Further
     commits update the PR. (`gh` is server-side; `git -C <main> …` from the worktree cwd is
     guard-inert.)
   - *Local / no remote:* there's no PR — keep committing on the branch.

3. **Self-review to convergence.** Self-review per `my-code-review` (a fresh sub-agent), address
   findings, and iterate — pushing fixes to the open draft — until a review surfaces nothing
   significant and you're confident it's ready for human review (`my-executing` owns this loop).

4. **Freshen, then mark ready — never auto-merge.** Bring the branch current:
   `git -C <main> pull --rebase`, then rebase your branch onto latest main and resolve conflicts.
   (If a push is rejected non-fast-forward, retry the rebase once, then surface.) Then:
   - *GitHub:* `gh pr ready` to mark the draft review-ready. Leave the PR **open**; surface the PR URL
     and a short "what to review" note. Do **not** run `gh pr merge`.
   - *Local / no remote:* **stop** — do not advance main. Tell me the branch is ready and summarize
     what to review.

5. **Merge only on my explicit approval, and only what's expected to deploy.** `main` reflects prod:
   never merge a change you don't expect to ship (here, to be `chezmoi apply`-ied). If it isn't
   deploy-ready, keep it a draft / on the branch.
   - *Repos I own ({{ .my.github_personal_owners | join ", " }}):* after I approve in-session,
     squash-merge. GitHub → `gh pr merge --squash --delete-branch`, then `git -C <main> pull --rebase`,
     and delete the local branch with `git branch -D <branch>` (squash leaves it "unmerged", so `-d`
     refuses). Local → `git -C <main> pull --rebase` (if it has a remote), `git -C <main> merge --squash
     <branch>` + one conventional commit, `git -C <main> push` (if it has a remote), then
     `git branch -D <branch>`.
   - *Work / shared (owner not mine):* I merge through the org's process; the agent never merges these.
   - *Unrecognized origin:* gather the facts (remote URL, owner, is it yours?), ask me how to
     integrate, then propose a `my-git` update so it's covered next time (see `my-agent-memory`).

6. **Cleanup — after an approved merge only.** Until the change is merged, **keep** the worktree (I may
   request changes — resume in it) and leave the `todo.txt` claim open. After merging, delete the local
   branch (step 5) and remove the worktree (`ExitWorktree action: remove`); the SessionEnd hook archives
   the todo claim. (A squash-merge isn't a fast-forward, so the branch isn't auto-reaped — the explicit
   `git branch -D` is what clears it.)

### Committing from a worktree when the root thread can't run Bash

When the root-thread guard blocks Bash in the main thread, a subagent can't commit in a worktree
because its cwd is pinned to main (the bash guard checks cwd *before* any inline `cd`). Sequence
that works:

1. **First subagent does the edits and `git worktree add`** (both allowed on main) but leaves the
   changes staged — it cannot commit from a cwd pinned to main.
2. **Root calls `EnterWorktree path: <abs worktree path>`** to move the root session's cwd into
   that worktree.
3. **Spawn a commit subagent** — it inherits the worktree cwd, so the bash guard goes inert and it
   can commit + merge back per the protocol above.

The `SessionEnd` cleanup (below) means the entered worktree is no longer reaped mid-session, so
this survives across turns.

{{- if hasPrefix "dot_claude/" $.chezmoi.sourceFile }}

### Claude Code create / exit mechanics

- Create: `EnterWorktree name: "$CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID.<task-slug>"`.
- Worktree path: `.claude/worktrees/<session-id>.<task-slug>`.
- Complete: `ExitWorktree action: remove` only after an approved merge; hand off per the
  integration/handoff/merge rules in steps 2–5 above.
- Auto-cleanup: the SessionEnd hook removes merged worktrees at session end and
  archives their todo.txt entries; prefer explicit `ExitWorktree` — it's a safety net,
  not a substitute.
- Human-only bypass: `touch .claude/worktree-exempt.$CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID` — agents
  must never create worktree exemption files.
{{- end }}
{{- if hasPrefix "dot_pi/" $.chezmoi.sourceFile }}

### Pi create / exit mechanics

- Create: call the `worktree_start` tool with a prompt or explicit branch name; the
  `@rezamonangg/pi-worktree` package creates the worktree and routes subsequent
  write/edit/bash calls into it via path rewriting.
- Worktree path: `.worktree/<branch>`, branch inferred from task type
  (feat/, fix/, docs/, refactor/, test/).
- The `worktree-guard.ts` extension blocks mutations until `worktree_start` succeeds;
  all `worktree_*` tools are always allowed.
- Complete: call `worktree_stop` (optionally `remove: true`) only after an approved merge;
  hand off per the integration/handoff/merge rules in steps 2–5 above.
- Human-only bypass: `touch .pi/worktree-exempt` — agents must never create worktree
  exemption files.
{{- end }}
